    a: "<b>LE (Locked motor / Error)</b> indicates the Direct Drive motor circuit reported a fault, but it's the most-misdiagnosed code on LG washers and almost never needs a full motor replacement on the first call. The Direct Drive motor circuit has <b>four distinct failure points</b>: the hall sensor (rotor position sensor), the stator winding, the rotor magnet assembly, and the inverter board. <b>The hall sensor accounts for the majority of LE codes we see</b>, and on WM3900, WM4000, and WM4500 series it's a standalone replaceable component accessible without removing the drum. We always test the hall sensor first, 10-minute step that costs $145-$215 if it's the failure. Replacing the full rotor/stator assembly based on the LE code alone (without hall sensor test) is the most common unnecessary expense in LG washer repair. We don't do that. If hall sensor tests good and other components fail, then we quote stator/rotor work ($385-$580) honestly. Try removing some clothes, redistributing the rest, and restarting the cycle first, about a third of LE codes clear here at no cost when caused by a heavily unbalanced load."
