<!-- 01 INTRO -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">01, About LG washer repair</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">LG washers are some of the most reliable in the US market, and the Direct Drive design changes how we diagnose every call.</h2>

    <p>LG Electronics is one of the two Korean appliance giants (alongside Samsung) dominating mid-tier and premium US washer installations. In our five-county SoCal service area, LG concentrates heavily in newer construction across Pasadena, Calabasas, Hidden Hills, the Inland Empire, and the Westside. WashTower vertical units appear constantly in Beverly Hills and Newport Beach renovation laundry rooms; standard WM front-loaders cover the rest.</p>

    <p>One LG washer reality shapes how we approach diagnostic calls: the <strong>Direct Drive motor</strong>. Unlike conventional washers with belts, pulleys, and transmissions that wear over time, LG's Direct Drive mounts the motor directly to the drum shaft. The result: typical service-life expectancy of 12-15 years on WM-series washers, far above industry average, provided the front bearing seal is replaced when the bearing starts to wear (around year 8 maintenance). The trade-off is in error code interpretation: when something goes wrong with the Direct Drive system, the LE code is the most-misdiagnosed appliance fault on the US market.</p>

    <p>The Direct Drive motor circuit has <strong>four distinct failure points</strong>: the hall sensor (rotor position), the stator winding, the rotor magnet assembly, and the inverter board. Replacing the full rotor/stator assembly based on the LE code alone, without testing the hall sensor first, is the most common unnecessary expense in LG washer repair. The hall sensor is a 10-minute test and a $145-$215 fix when it's the cause; the full motor is $385-$580. We always test the hall sensor first.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 02 COMMON PROBLEMS -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">02, Common LG washer problems</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What we see fail most often on LG washers, and how we diagnose each.</h2>

    <p class="lead">LG washer service calls cluster around five symptom categories. Each has a predictable diagnostic tree.</p>

    <ul class="bullet-list">
      <li><strong>OE error / not draining:</strong> About 50% of OE calls resolve at the debris filter clear (bottom-front access panel) at no parts cost. Remaining 50% are drain pump failures ($245-$385) or, rarely, drain hose installation issues.</li>
      <li><strong>LE error / motor fault:</strong> Hall sensor first, accounts for the majority of LE codes ($145-$215 fix). Only after hall sensor and inverter board are ruled out do we quote full Direct Drive motor work ($385-$580). About a third of LE codes clear by redistributing an unbalanced load at no cost.</li>
      <li><strong>Door won't open / dE error:</strong> Door latch motor or door switch failure. The latch motor is the more common failure on WM-series ($145-$245 replacement). Sometimes the symptom is post-cycle water remaining in the drum (which engages the safety lockout), clearing the OE drain symptom resolves the dE secondarily.</li>
      <li><strong>Water leaking from the door:</strong> Door boot / bellows seal tear. Year 7-9 wear item on LG front-loaders. The boot accumulates debris, mildew, and eventually tears from repeated flex. Bellows replacement runs $285-$425, sealant doesn't fix a torn bellows.</li>
      <li><strong>Loud rumble or grinding during spin:</strong> Front bearing seal weeping moisture into the bearing, accelerating wear. Year 8 maintenance window. Replacing the bearing and front seal as a set ($385-$580) extends washer life to 12-15 years total. Catching it at this stage prevents drum damage that pushes the repair to $585-$880.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>LG ThinQ Wi-Fi connectivity rarely fails in isolation, when "the app says my washer is broken," the underlying fault is one of the five categories above, surfaced through the app rather than caused by it.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 03 ERROR CODES -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">03, LG washer error codes decoded</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What the codes on your LG washer actually mean.</h2>

    <p>LG washer error codes appear on the front panel or through the LG ThinQ app on connected models. The codes that come up most often on our service calls:</p>

    <div class="error-table">
      <div class="error-row"><strong>OE</strong>, Outlet (drain) error. Filter clog (50% of cases), drain hose, or drain pump failure ($245-$385).</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>LE</strong>, Locked motor / Direct Drive fault. <b>Hall sensor first</b> ($145-$215). Then inverter board, then full motor. Or simply unbalanced overload, try redistributing.</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>UE</strong>, Unbalanced load. Redistribute clothes; 80% resolve at no cost. Persistent UE points to shock absorbers ($185-$285).</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>IE</strong>, Inlet (water supply) error. Check supply valves at the wall, hose kinks, inlet screen filters before quoting inlet valve replacement ($185-$285).</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>dE / dE1 / dE2</strong>, Door error / door not closed. Door switch, latch motor, or post-cycle water lockout ($145-$245).</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>tE</strong>, Heating system fault (steam-cycle WM washers). Heating element, thermistor, or thermal fuse.</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>FE</strong>, Overflow detected. Pressure switch, water inlet valve stuck open, or sensor fault.</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>PE</strong>, Pressure switch / water level sensor fault. $125-$185 sensor replacement on most models.</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>CE</strong>, Current overload to the motor. Often triggered by foreign object jamming the drum; sometimes points to motor winding fault.</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>SE</strong>, Sensor error (Hall sensor or rotor position sensor). Direct hall sensor diagnostic, $145-$215 fix.</div>
      <div class="error-row"><strong>Sud / SUDs</strong>, Excess suds detected. Use HE detergent only and reduce dose. Not a hardware fault.</div>
    </div>

    <p>Reset procedure for any LG washer showing an error: kill the breaker for 60-90 seconds. About <strong>15-20% of error codes clear on a single power cycle at no parts cost</strong>. If the code returns, that's the diagnostic, and the table above is your starting point.</p>
  </div>
</section>

